# Why i did not use One-Hot Encoding (OHE)

One-Hot Encoding converts a categorical variable into multiple binary columns (0 or 1).

| borough_y | Manhattan | Brooklyn | Queens |
| --------- | --------- | -------- | ------ |
| Manhattan | 1         | 0        | 0      |
| Brooklyn  | 0         | 1        | 0      |

Although OHE is commonly used, it has several drawbacks in this case:

Sparsity Problem
OHE creates many columns where most values are 0 and only a few are 1. This makes the dataset sparse and increases dimensionality unnecessarily.

Loss of Information
OHE only indicates category membership. It does not capture the relationship between the category and the target variable (sale_price).

Poor Signal for Linear Models
Linear models work better when features have a continuous numerical relationship with the target.
OHE produces binary (0,1) features, which may not capture price differences effectively.

Because of these limitations, i used target encoding (mean encoding) instead.

# Initial Approach: Simple Mean Encoding

I first calculated the average sale price for each borough:

variation = df.groupby('borough_y')['sale_price'].mean()
df['borough_mean_price'] = df['borough_y'].map(variation)

This converts the categorical feature into a meaningful numerical value.

Example:

borough_y	mean sale_price
Manhattan	2100000
Brooklyn	1500000
Queens	980000

Now the feature represents economic information about each borough, which is useful for price prediction.

Problem with Simple Mean Encoding

However, this approach has a limitation.

Different categories may have different numbers of observations.

Example:

borough	houses	mean price
Manhattan	3000	2,100,000
Small area	3	3,000,000

The small category has only 3 samples, so its mean price is unstable and unreliable.

This problem is called:

High variance in small groups

A linear model may wrongly assume that the small category is extremely expensive simply because of a few samples.

Solution: Smoothed Target Encoding

To make the encoding more reliable, I used smoothing.

The idea is to combine the group mean with the global mean of the dataset.

Formula:

        Encoded value = (group_mean*Count + global_mean*k) / (count + k) 
    
    Where:

        group_mean = average price of the category

        count = number of observations in that category

        global_mean = overall average sale price in the dataset

        k = smoothing parameter (controls how much we trust small groups)

Benefits of This Method

    Reduces noise from categories with very small sample sizes

    Encodes meaningful price information into the feature

    Produces continuous numerical features, which work better with linear regression

    Avoids the sparsity problem caused by one-hot encoding

# Created a standard scaler function
    > Applied log transformation over the right skewed data and then applied the standard scaling
    > Standardization (Standard Scaler) and normalization are used to bring features to a similar scale so 
    that no single feature dominates the model just because it has larger numerical values. 
    Many machine learning algorithms, especially linear regression, gradient descent-based models, and distance-based models, 
    perform better when the input features are on comparable scales. 
    Scaling also improves numerical stability and helps the model converge faster during training. By standardizing or normalizing the data,
    we ensure that each feature contributes more fairly to the learning process.

